<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="82" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1340,2013]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1340,1365]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Externally very similar to the preceding species, but this new species can be distinguished by its carmine basic coloration; different color pattern of coxae (
<figureCitation box="[810,879,1376,1401]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1372,1394]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,1348]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[150,1436,193,1350]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Holotypes of Hypseloecus species, pleura in left-lateral view, each including all coxae and scent efferent system." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290613/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">
Fig. 
<number box="[863,879,1376,1401]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation box="[892,974,1376,1401]" captionStart="TABLE 1. A" captionStartId="6.[119,219,498,520]" captionTargetBox="[120,1871,646,1706]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. A list of convenient diagnostic characters to aid identification of Thai Hypseloecus species." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF49DCE2BC7BD925FFD5FE2E1321FDC4" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" tableUuid="DF49DCE2BC7BD925FFD5FE2E1321FDC4">
Table 
<number box="[961,974,1376,1400]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
); and widely reddish femora. The dorsal scalelike setae of all available specimens were probably rubbed off after capture.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="82" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1340,2013]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1448,1473]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[356,414,1448,1472]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">Male</emphasis>
. COLORATION AND VESTITURE: Body generally carmine or reddish brown. Head reddish maroon, rather shining, with yellow lateral margins along eyes. Antenna uniformly pale or yellowish brown, slender; apex of segment I sometimes tinged with red; segments III and IV dark brown; the former with whitish extreme base. Labium shiny reddish brown. Pronotum carmine, usually widely infuscate; scutellum pale reddish maroon; pleura as in 
<figureCitation box="[491,562,1592,1617]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1372,1394]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,1348]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[150,1436,193,1350]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Holotypes of Hypseloecus species, pleura in left-lateral view, each including all coxae and scent efferent system." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290613/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">
Fig. 
<number box="[546,562,1592,1617]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
; ostiolar peritreme yellowish white. Hemelytron carmine with a broad dark stripe each on corium and clavus; membrane grayish brown, with pale reddish veins and irregular, pale, semitransparent portion at middle. Coxae as in 
<tableCitation box="[719,808,1664,1689]" captionStart="TABLE 1. A" captionStartId="6.[119,219,498,520]" captionTargetBox="[120,1871,646,1706]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. A list of convenient diagnostic characters to aid identification of Thai Hypseloecus species." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF49DCE2BC7BD925FFD5FE2E1321FDC4" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" tableUuid="DF49DCE2BC7BD925FFD5FE2E1321FDC4">
Table 
<number box="[793,808,1664,1688]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
. All femora reddish brown, each speckled with pale maculae; all tibiae with rather clear, reddish brown annulations; protibia with an orange-red stripe anteriorly. Abdomen reddish brown or darker. STRUCTURE: As in generic description (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh" box="[1139,1425,1736,1761]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2011) Santalalean-feeding plant bugs: ten new species in the genus Hypseloecus Reuter from Australia and South Africa (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae): their hosts and placement in the Pilophorini. Australian Journal of Entomology, 50, 365 - 392. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1440 - 6055.2011.00829. x" type="journal article" year="2011">
Schuh &amp; Menard, 
<number box="[1365,1425,1736,1760]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[151,257,1772,1796]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[272,341,1772,1797]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1697,1719]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,436,1678]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,425,1691]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male genitalia of Hypseloecus katrinae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/287970/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">
Fig. 
<number box="[324,341,1772,1796]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
): Right paramere bulbous. Endosoma J-shaped, long, slender, with a bifurcate process at apical 
<number box="[1414,1425,1772,1796]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[151,165,1808,1832]" pageId="7" pageNumber="82" value="3.0">3</number>
portion. 
<emphasis box="[267,351,1808,1832]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="82">Female</emphasis>
. Similar coloration and structure to male.
</paragraph>
